<p><b>Intel Corporation</b> is an American <a href="/wiki/semiconductor" title="semiconductor">semiconductor</a> company. While most notably known for their development of <a href="/wiki/microprocessors" class="mw-redirect" title="microprocessors">microprocessors</a> and <a href="/wiki/x86" title="x86">x86</a>, Intel also designs and manufactures other <a href="/wiki/integrated_circuit" title="integrated circuit">integrated circuits</a> including <a href="/w/index.php?title=flash_memory&action=edit&redlink=1" class="new" title="flash memory (page does not exist)">flash memory</a>, <a href="/w/index.php?title=network_interface_controller&action=edit&redlink=1" class="new" title="network interface controller (page does not exist)">network interface controllers</a>, <a href="/w/index.php?title=GPU&action=edit&redlink=1" class="new" title="GPU (page does not exist)">GPUs</a>, <a href="/w/index.php?title=chipset&action=edit&redlink=1" class="new" title="chipset (page does not exist)">chipsets</a>, motherboards, and computers.
</p><p>In addition to <a href="/wiki/x86" title="x86">x86</a>, Intel used to also design and manufacture <a href="/wiki/ARM" class="mw-redirect" title="ARM">ARM</a>-based chips as well as embed <a href="/w/index.php?title=ARC&action=edit&redlink=1" class="new" title="ARC (page does not exist)">ARC</a>-based cores in their products. While they no longer sell such chips, they still use ARM processors in various products (e.g. in their FPGAs) as well as still retain full a architectural level ARM license allowing them to design and sell their own ARM devices should they wish to.
</p>
